<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06007075 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06007075 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Associated Press; STUMBLING BLOCK -- Chicago's Jocelyn Lemieuxtrips over the Kings' Bob Kudelski during the Blackhawks' 3-1 loss.  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  PROFESSIONAL; HOCKEY; CLUB; GAME; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Goaltender Daniel Berthiaume stopped 37 shots and Jim Thomson scored his firstgoal since the 1988-89 season, lifting the Los Angeles Kings over the ChicagoBlackhawks 3-1 Sunday.;    The Kings' fourth win on their five-game tripboosted Los Angeles to within two points of first-place Calgary in the SmytheDivision.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  BERTHIAUME, KINGS STOP CHICAGO  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  NHL Roundup  </MEMO><TEXT>     It was the second strong performance for Berthiaume against the Blackhawks,whom he stopped 2-0 with a 40-save performance Nov. 4.;    &quot;The guys playedextremely well in front of me,&quot; Berthiaume said. &quot;They let me see the first(shot), then got the puck out of there. The way we played this trip, hopefullywe're back on track. This is how it was in the beginning of the season.&quot;;   With 16 minutes, 11 seconds gone in the second period, Thomson -- recalledfrom New Haven on Friday -- blasted in a 20-footer to break a 1-1 tie. It wasThomson's first goal, and only the third in his career, since he scored twofor the Washington Capitals during the 1988-89 season.;    Blackhawks CoachMike Keenan benched star defenseman Chris Chelios for the final eight minutesof the second period and the opening 15 minutes of the third.;    &quot;You sitpeople for different reasons,&quot; Keenan said. &quot;We didn't get any production fromour power play (in seven chances). I think that's a pretty good reason rightthere.&quot;;    Chelios responded, &quot;It was pretty embarrassing, but there'snothing I can do.&quot;;  CANADIENS 6, PENGUINS 3: Defenseman Jean-JacquesDaigneault scored his first goal of the season and set up two others to leadMontreal to a home-ice victory over Pittsburgh.;    Guy Carbonneau had twogoals and Stephan Lebeau, Eric Desjardins and Brent Gilchrist also scored asMontreal won its third consecutive game.;    Montreal has an all-time homerecord of 44-4-5 against Pittsburgh.;    The victory moved Montreal to withinone point of Adams Division-leading Boston, but the Bruins have played twofewer games.;  ETC.: Defenseman Gerald Diduck has walked out on the Canadiens,and Coach Pat Burns said Diduck will not return &quot;as long as I'm coach.&quot;Diduck, acquired in a preseason trade with the New York Islanders, had anargument with Burns on Saturday after learning he would not play that nightagainst the Quebec Nordiques. He left the team and did not report for Sunday'sgame against Pittsburgh. Burns said Diduck would be traded or sent to theminors. . . . The Edmonton Oilers, behind the outstanding goaltending of KariTakko, defeated the touring Soviet-Central Red Army 4-2 in Edmonton, Alberta.It was the Red Army team's first loss in five games on its NHL tour. . . . Inanother exhibition, Zdeno Ciger scored with 11 seconds remaining in the thirdperiod to give the New Jersey Devils a 2-2 tie with Dynamo Moscow in EastRutherford, N.J.  </TEXT><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910107  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  January  </MONTH><PG.COL>  7C  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  505  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Monday January 7, 199100007075,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>